The behavior, persistence, and ecological impacts of nanoscale pigments are largely determined by the physical, chemical, and biological transformations that they undergo. In aquatic systems, such changes in the distribution of pigments resulting from physical processes during degradation (e.g., aggregation and sedimentation) may enrich sediments with pigments and thus influence benthic ecosystems. Different chemical transformations, including oxidation, reduction, and reactions with natural organic matter, can change the structural and reactive properties of pigments, affecting their toxicity, mobility, and bioavailability. These transformations reveal the importance of considering the behaviors of nanoscale pigments in the environment when assessing their potential risks to the environment and health. Understanding these processes is essential for risk assessment frameworks and guidance for sustainable management strategies leveraging the One Health paradigm that supports the safe use of nanoscale pigments, while protecting environmental and human health.[

